data.reasoningText:
It seems there's a pre-existing error with `DateTime` — the `Order` class at line 11 doesn't have `using System;`. Let me check again more carefully.

Looking at AppDbContext.cs:
```csharp
using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;
class AppDbContext : DbContext
{
    public DbSet<Order> Orders => Set<Order>();
    protected override void OnModelCreating(ModelBuilder modelBuilder)
    {
        modelBuilder.Entity<Order>().HasData(
            new Order { Id = 1, CreatedAt = DateTime.UtcNow });
    }
}
class Order { public int Id { get; set; } public DateTime CreatedAt { get; set; } }
```

The `DateTime` type needs `using System;` or the project needs implicit usings enabled. Let me check the csproj — it doesn't have `<ImplicitUsings>enable</ImplicitUsings>`, so `System` isn't implicitly imported. Though in .NET 6+, implicit usings are typically enabled by default in new projects, so I should verify what's actually configured.

Looking at the csproj more carefully, it doesn't specify `<ImplicitUsings>` at all. The default behavior depends on the SDK — in .NET 6+ projects, implicit usings are usually enabled, but that's not guaranteed. The real issue is that the `Order` class uses `DateTime` without a `using System;` directive, and the file only has `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;`. This looks like a pre-existing problem in the code. Let me try running `dotnet restore` and then building to see if that clears up the issue. The `DateTime` error is strange since it should be available globally, but it could be a NuGet restoration problem. I'm also wondering if the .NET 11 SDK being used to build a .NET 8 project is causing complications, though that shouldn't normally be an issue. Let me just proceed with the build and see if updating the target framework resolves it. it should be on by default. Let me try running `dotnet restore` first to ensure all dependencies are properly resolved, then attempt the build.

